Pathophysiology of heart failure 

Tuesday, May 30, 2017 

4:18 PM 

Define cardiac output and how it is controlled (revision) 

Cardiac output = Stroke volume x Heart rate 

This is controlled by sympathetic and parasympathetic innervation of the heart, blood vessels, etc. 

 

Define ejection fraction and describe its normal ranges 

Ejection fraction refers to the percentage of blood that is ejected out of the ventricles with each contraction. Ejection fraction = Stroke volume/End diastolic volume. Normal ejection fractions range from 55% to 70%.  

 

Define and distinguish systolic and diastolic failure 

Systolic failure occurs when ventricular ejection fraction is less than 40%. Relaxation (filling) is normal. Stroke volume is reduced. This is caused by conditions impacting myocardial contractility (ischemic heart disease), creating more work for the heart such as via volume overload (valvular insufficiency), or hypertension.  

 

Diastolic failure occurs when ventricular ejection fraction is normal, but relaxation (filling) is reduced and stroke volume is reduced or normal. This is caused by conditions that impede heart expansion (pericardial effusion), reduce ventricular compliance (myocardial fibrosis), increased wall thickness and reduce chamber size (hypertrophy), or delayed relaxation (ischemic heart disease).  

 

Right vs left sided heart failure 

 

 

Define preload, afterload and contractility, and briefly describe the effect of each on cardiac output 

Preload: refers to the stretch on the sarcomeres just prior to the initiation of systolic contraction. The more blood there is in the chamber prior to systole, the more the sarcomeres are stretched (the higher the systole). The higher the preload, the higher the stroke volume by the Frank-Starling mechanism.  

 

Afterload: refers to the pressure which opposes the ejection of blood out of the chamber, influenced by vascular resistance. Afterload results in the normal ejection fraction being at around 60%. A higher afterload will decrease cardiac output, whilst a lower afterload increases cardiac output.  

 

Contractility: the intrinsic length of the ventricle (cardiomyocytes), independent of loading conditions. Increased contractility would cause a higher ejection fraction.  

 

Define the normal atrial and ventricular pressures during the cardiac cycle 

Atrial pressure ranges from 5-15mmHg throughout. Ventricular pressure ranges from 0-10mmHg during diastole, but reaches around 120mmHg during systole.  

 

Briefly describe the relationship of jugular venous pressure and its waveform to right atrial events 

 

A wave- right atrial contraction 

X wave- right atrial relaxation 

V wave- passive atrial filling 

Y wave- atrial emptying with opening of the tricuspid valve 

 

Briefly describe the physiologic events in systolic failure that lead to pulmonary edema 

In systolic failure, impaired left ventricular contractility reduces cardiac output. This causes an increase in left ventricular filling pressure and left atrial pressure. This increases the hydrostatic force in the pulmonary circulation, such that plasma flows out of the capillaries to result in pulmonary edema. Furthermore, the original decrease in cardiac output activates the RAAS system to increase water retention, and the sympathetic system to cause vasodilation, ultimately promoting pulmonary edema.  

 

Describe the compensatory mechanisms in heart failure (sympathetic reflexes, RAAS, Frank-Starling mechanism, and hypertrophy) 

Sympathetic reflexes: In heart failure, cardiac output decreases. Sympathetic reflexes increase heart rate, cardiac contractility, and vascular tone through baroreceptors. Furthermore in increased right atrial pressure (systolic dysfunction), the Bainbridge (atrial) reflex occurs. Atrial and pulmonary vein stretch (volume) receptors are activated, leading to sympathetic action.  

 

RAAS: 

 

ADH and aldosterone help increase filling volume of the ventricles, causing the heart walls to stretch further. As per the Frank-Starling mechanism, this increases stroke volume. 

 

Frank-Starling mechanism: 

Increased venous return increases filling pressure, which stretches the heart walls to result in increased contraction. This increases stroke volume. 

 

Hypertrophy: 

Hypertrophy increases the force of contraction to increase cardiac output. It also increases the preload pressure by reducing the ventricular space. 

 

Myocardial remodeling: 

The death of myocytes due to overworking, and other pathogenic causes (eg after myocardial infarct), results in the proliferation of non-contractile cells eg fibroblasts, macrophages, vascular smooth muscles cells, and endothelial cells.
